==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Serf
<hw>Serf</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>serus</ets> servant, slave; akin to <ets>servare</ets> to protect,
preserve, observe, and perhaps originally, a client, a man under one's
protection. Cf. <er>Serve</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>A servant
or slave employed in husbandry, and in some countries attached to the
soil and transferred with it, as formerly in Russia.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In England, at least from the reign of Henry II, one only, and
that the inferior species [of villeins], existed . . . But by the
customs of France and Germany, persons in this abject state seem to have
been called <qex>serfs</qex>, and distinguished from
<qex>villeins</qex>, who were only bound to fixed payments and duties in
respect of their lord, though, as it seems, without any legal redress if
injured by him.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Serf</er>, <er>Slave</er>.</syn> <usage> A
<xex>slave</xex> is the absolute property of his master, and may be sold
in any way. A <xex>serf</xex>, according to the strict sense of the
term, is one bound to work on a certain estate, and thus attached to the
soil, and sold with it into the service of whoever purchases the
land.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Serfdom</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Serfage</ent>⟦br⟧
